00:00:21.030 --> 00:00:24.710
PROFESSOR: Today, as I mentioned
to you in last lecture,

00:00:24.710 --> 00:00:27.640
we're going to really be
focusing in quite some depth

00:00:27.640 --> 00:00:29.370
into this paper by Sunney Xie.

00:00:29.370 --> 00:00:33.940
So I would say that it is one
of my all time favorite papers.

00:00:33.940 --> 00:00:35.490
And in particular
from the standpoint

00:00:35.490 --> 00:00:37.380
of discussing a
paper in class, I

00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:40.190
think it is
absolutely wonderful.

00:00:40.190 --> 00:00:43.140
It is, I think, clearly written.

00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:46.270
It explains why that
did all these things.

00:00:46.270 --> 00:00:49.130
And they checked all
sorts of possible sources

00:00:49.130 --> 00:00:52.390
of perhaps being lead astray.

00:00:52.390 --> 00:00:54.130
And I think it was a
huge amount of work,

00:00:54.130 --> 00:00:57.410
and it was a technical tour
de force when it came out.

00:00:57.410 --> 00:01:01.450
So before this, I would say
single molecule biophysics,

00:01:01.450 --> 00:01:05.540
by which I mean both single
molecule fluorescence,

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:08.480
i.e., detection, as well as
single molecule manipulation,

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:12.590
were almost exclusively
in vitro techniques.

00:01:12.590 --> 00:01:15.320
So we took purified
components, and then we

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:18.350
studied the fluorescence,
or the mechanical properties

00:01:18.350 --> 00:01:22.681
and so forth, of these molecules
in the equivalent of a test

00:01:22.681 --> 00:01:23.180
tube.

00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:25.500
But really, in glass
slides, where we just

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:28.082
had to purified components,
so no know living cells.

00:01:28.082 --> 00:01:30.290
And I think we got a lot of
insight into the dynamics

00:01:30.290 --> 00:01:33.050
of molecular motors,
transcription, translation,

00:01:33.050 --> 00:01:35.040
and so forth.

00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:37.200
And I think that many
of us in the field

00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:42.700
thought that this paper was
essentially not possible.

00:01:42.700 --> 00:01:47.030
I did my Ph.D in the
single molecule area,

00:01:47.030 --> 00:01:50.140
from of 2002 to
2005, I graduated.

00:01:50.140 --> 00:01:53.230
And indeed, I did a
little bit of work

00:01:53.230 --> 00:01:55.830
in this area of single
molecule fluorescence,

00:01:55.830 --> 00:01:58.070
and I was basically
unsuccessful.

00:01:58.070 --> 00:02:00.860
Even just doing this kind
of an in vitro setting.

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:05.152
My lab is [INAUDIBLE],
we did primarily

00:02:05.152 --> 00:02:06.360
single molecule manipulation.

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:10.550
We were playing with the
single molecule fluorescence .

00:02:10.550 --> 00:02:13.510
And eventually, people in
the lab got it to work.

00:02:13.510 --> 00:02:16.540
But I would say that my foray
into it was maybe unsuccessful.

00:02:16.540 --> 00:02:19.880
So I had a very healthy
respect for the challenges

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:22.520
that are involved in doing
single molecule fluorescence.

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:28.142
And the thought of doing this
in live cells was very scary.

00:02:28.142 --> 00:02:29.600
And I'd say that
many of us thought

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:30.900
it was not going to work.

00:02:30.900 --> 00:02:33.940
And indeed, this
project was one--

00:02:33.940 --> 00:02:36.877
and the general goal of
studying a single molecule

00:02:36.877 --> 00:02:38.460
dynamics in living
cells, is something

00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:39.920
that's Sunney's group had
been working on, I think,

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:40.930
for many years.

00:02:40.930 --> 00:02:43.060
And it indeed was very hard.

00:02:43.060 --> 00:02:45.150
But then there were
these two papers

00:02:45.150 --> 00:02:47.850
they came out, both from
Sunnye's lab actually.

00:02:47.850 --> 00:02:51.380
And they came out both, i
think, in January of 2006,

00:02:51.380 --> 00:02:53.740
one in science, one in
Nature, demonstrating

00:02:53.740 --> 00:02:55.850
not one way of doing
this, but rather two

00:02:55.850 --> 00:02:59.897
ways of getting single molecule
dynamics inside living cells.

00:02:59.897 --> 00:03:02.230
So today, obviously, we're
going to be primarily talking

00:03:02.230 --> 00:03:03.872
about this paper by [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:03.872 --> 00:03:05.580
But if you're interested
in these things,

00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:07.788
I encourage you to check
out [INAUDIBLE] paper, which

00:03:07.788 --> 00:03:11.120
also published, [INAUDIBLE],
at the same time.

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:14.940
And that was based on a
microfluidic assay, where

00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:16.440
instead of doing
the single molecule

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:19.850
fluorescence within
cells, instead by trapping

00:03:19.850 --> 00:03:22.170
the cells in small
volumes, and then using

00:03:22.170 --> 00:03:25.270
more traditional enzymatic
assays, such as this beta

00:03:25.270 --> 00:03:27.790
[INAUDIBLE] assay,
enclosed in a small volume,

00:03:27.790 --> 00:03:30.347
it's almost possible to
study, once again, these sort

00:03:30.347 --> 00:03:32.572
of busting dynamics in E. coli.

00:03:32.572 --> 00:03:34.530
And also they did it in
yeast, and demonstrated

00:03:34.530 --> 00:03:37.970
that it's kind of a
generally practical assay.

00:03:37.970 --> 00:03:39.680
So if you're interested
in those papers,

00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:41.770
I encourage you to check it out.

00:03:41.770 --> 00:03:44.980
But for me, this was really
an eye-opening thing.

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:49.400
So I graduated with my
Ph.D. in December of 2005,

00:03:49.400 --> 00:03:55.320
and then I went to a conference
in Cambridge, England,

00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:57.660
where where Sunney
presented this work.

00:03:57.660 --> 00:04:01.450
And I think that it really blew
many of our minds, this idea

00:04:01.450 --> 00:04:04.420
that you could start to get this
sort of data within live cells.

00:04:04.420 --> 00:04:07.766
And indeed, Sunney's group
over the next five years

00:04:07.766 --> 00:04:09.390
did a whole series
of what I'd consider

00:04:09.390 --> 00:04:12.380
to be beautiful studies,
probing, for example,

00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:16.480
the dynamics of this [INAUDIBLE]
repressor binding, unbindings

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:20.750
onto this promoter,
the search process.

00:04:20.750 --> 00:04:21.250
Yeah.

00:04:21.250 --> 00:04:23.040
A whole slew of, I think,
really beautiful things.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:24.500
So we're not going
to have the chance

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:26.250
to go over all those
papers in this class,

00:04:26.250 --> 00:04:30.990
but I encourage you
to look at them.

00:04:30.990 --> 00:04:34.195
Can somebody say what
the primary challenge

00:04:34.195 --> 00:04:37.320
is with doing single
molecule fluorescence

00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:39.520
in these live cells?

00:04:48.130 --> 00:04:50.230
So why is it that
I did not think

00:04:50.230 --> 00:04:52.460
that this was going to work?

00:04:52.460 --> 00:04:57.360
And now, you're going to
have to give an argument that

00:04:57.360 --> 00:04:58.583
ends up not being true.

00:04:58.583 --> 00:05:04.308
But why is it that this is
such a hard thing to do.

00:05:04.308 --> 00:05:05.724
Yeah?

00:05:05.724 --> 00:05:08.084
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
laser at the cell

00:05:08.084 --> 00:05:09.500
but you can't kill the cell?

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:09.830
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:05:09.830 --> 00:05:10.329
OK.

00:05:10.329 --> 00:05:18.030
So one is that there's
laser, the cell, and then

00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:19.240
there's a big question mark.

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:21.910
Is this going to be OK?

00:05:21.910 --> 00:05:25.550
And indeed, we certainly
know that at one limit,

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:28.200
it's not going to be OK.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:32.530
If you take the lasers at
Los Alamos National Lab,

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:34.144
you can vaporize the cell.

00:05:34.144 --> 00:05:36.060
So it's certainly enough
power, and the cell's

00:05:36.060 --> 00:05:37.960
going to be dead for sure.

00:05:37.960 --> 00:05:39.485
And so the question
is maybe, oh,

00:05:39.485 --> 00:05:42.590
can you dial down the
laser power enough to get--

00:05:42.590 --> 00:05:44.840
and indeed, this is something
that they talk about,

00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:47.630
their strategy in this paper.

00:05:47.630 --> 00:05:50.090
Other challenges, problems?

00:05:50.090 --> 00:05:51.850
AUDIENCE: Many molecules.

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:54.760
PROFESSOR: Right. so the
principle of many molecules.

00:05:54.760 --> 00:05:57.650
So we have to figure out
some way of separating them,

00:05:57.650 --> 00:05:59.350
either temporarily or spatially.

00:05:59.350 --> 00:06:02.130
Indeed in this paper,
they actually do both.

00:06:05.250 --> 00:06:06.580
We say many molecules.

00:06:06.580 --> 00:06:07.860
And of course, we have to
decide what we mean by this.

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:09.734
Because ultimately,
we're interested in doing

00:06:09.734 --> 00:06:12.380
single molecule measurements.

00:06:12.380 --> 00:06:15.270
But then, of course, of the
plural of single is many.

00:06:15.270 --> 00:06:19.427
How many is too many for
us to study, and so forth?

00:06:19.427 --> 00:06:21.760
The question here is maybe
like, how to separate, right?

00:06:31.330 --> 00:06:34.757
What are other
challenges in this?

00:06:34.757 --> 00:06:35.590
AUDIENCE: Diffusion.

00:06:35.590 --> 00:06:36.298
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:06:36.298 --> 00:06:37.240
There's diffusion.

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:40.211
So we're going to talk
more about this, for sure.

00:06:40.211 --> 00:06:41.710
Well, actually, all
of these things,

00:06:41.710 --> 00:06:42.793
we're going to talk about.

00:06:42.793 --> 00:06:43.400
Diffusion.

00:06:43.400 --> 00:06:46.790
And why is this a
problem, though?

00:06:46.790 --> 00:06:47.290
Right.

00:06:47.290 --> 00:06:51.560
So it's diffusion is maybe fast.

00:06:51.560 --> 00:06:55.552
And so this is going to end
up being relevant for kind

00:06:55.552 --> 00:06:59.120
of signal to noise reasons.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:01.955
So what's the signal
and what's the noise?

00:07:13.992 --> 00:07:15.470
AUDIENCE: Autofluorescence.

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:15.590
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:07:15.590 --> 00:07:16.756
So there's autofluorescence.

00:07:16.756 --> 00:07:21.390
So in particular, this noise
is autofluorescence from what?

00:07:28.264 --> 00:07:29.809
AUDIENCE: From the cell.

00:07:29.809 --> 00:07:30.850
PROFESSOR: From the cell.

00:07:30.850 --> 00:07:31.349
Right.

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:40.996
And what's the signal,
just to be clear here?

00:07:40.996 --> 00:07:43.217
AUDIENCE: Photons
from [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:43.217 --> 00:07:43.925
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:07:43.925 --> 00:07:47.115
So it's photons from, in this
case, the GFP-like molecule.

00:07:47.115 --> 00:07:48.520
Yeah?

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:51.920
So we want to do single
molecule measurements.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:54.590
We want to be able
to measure or detect

00:07:54.590 --> 00:07:57.830
the fluorescence coming
from this single fluorescent

00:07:57.830 --> 00:07:59.240
protein.

00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:01.600
Now the question is, if
it's a single molecule,

00:08:01.600 --> 00:08:03.350
does that mean that
it's going to send out

00:08:03.350 --> 00:08:04.225
just a single photon?

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:08.167
No.

00:08:08.167 --> 00:08:09.750
Maybe they come out
as single photons.

00:08:09.750 --> 00:08:13.410
But we can detect them.

00:08:13.410 --> 00:08:17.090
Now the challenge in,
in some ways surprising,

00:08:17.090 --> 00:08:21.450
is not that the number
of photons is so small.

00:08:21.450 --> 00:08:24.310
Does anybody have any
rough sense of maybe

00:08:24.310 --> 00:08:28.125
how many photons are we
collecting from each of these?

00:08:28.125 --> 00:08:29.460
AUDIENCE: Many thousands.

00:08:29.460 --> 00:08:30.170
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:08:30.170 --> 00:08:31.960
I'd say many thousands.

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:35.090
In particular-- so we'll
say many thousands.

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:43.610
It could be even 10 to
the 4 per second or so.

00:08:43.610 --> 00:08:46.300
It depends on the
laser intensity.

00:08:46.300 --> 00:08:48.630
Many thousands of
photons collected.

00:08:53.013 --> 00:08:53.961
Yes?

00:08:53.961 --> 00:08:55.460
AUDIENCE: That's
before [INAUDIBLE].

00:08:55.460 --> 00:08:56.170
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:08:56.170 --> 00:08:58.280
That's right.

00:08:58.280 --> 00:09:01.869
And indeed, the stronger
the intensity of the laser

00:09:01.869 --> 00:09:03.910
light that you illuminate
with, the faster you're

00:09:03.910 --> 00:09:05.910
going to collect the
photons, but in general, it

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:10.100
won't increase the total number
of photons that you collect.

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:13.910
So in these sorts
of situations, you

00:09:13.910 --> 00:09:18.240
might get, say-- we'll say
10 to the 4, plus or minus

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:21.260
in order of magnitude,
photons per second.

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:23.630
And they might
last for, depending

00:09:23.630 --> 00:09:26.255
on how-- for 30 seconds or so.

00:09:26.255 --> 00:09:29.200
And of course, we'll look at the
actual numbers in this paper.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:31.880
But in many of
these situations--

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:33.925
times 10 to 100 seconds.

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:41.760
In this case, it
actually bleached faster.

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:42.540
Right.

00:09:42.540 --> 00:09:44.519
But we'll see.

00:09:44.519 --> 00:09:46.060
Well, you might be
able to get also--

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:50.956
if you use organic
dyes and other-- right.

00:09:50.956 --> 00:09:52.830
But this gives you some
sense of that there's

00:09:52.830 --> 00:09:55.079
a fair number of photons
that you could, in principle,

00:09:55.079 --> 00:09:56.580
collect from a single molecule.

00:09:58.599 --> 00:10:00.390
Now, of course, you
might be worried, well,

00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:03.430
these are the photons that
you shine on your camera.

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:06.760
But then your camera
won't pick up all of them.

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:08.610
The way that we
think about this is

00:10:08.610 --> 00:10:11.410
by what's known as the
quantum efficiency.

00:10:11.410 --> 00:10:14.510
Quantum efficiency
tells us basically

00:10:14.510 --> 00:10:20.020
this is the fraction
of photons detected.

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:24.725
But with modern cameras,
actually, this thing

00:10:24.725 --> 00:10:25.690
is approximately one.

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:32.350
So it's 0.9 maybe
with modern cameras,

00:10:32.350 --> 00:10:37.010
which is for our
purposes, basically one.

00:10:37.010 --> 00:10:39.150
Which means that you
can detect, actually,

00:10:39.150 --> 00:10:43.540
the majority of the photons
that are hitting your camera.

00:10:43.540 --> 00:10:46.130
From that standpoint,
the number of photons

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:49.270
is not actually the problem.

00:10:49.270 --> 00:10:53.970
You can collect many
thousands of photons.

00:10:53.970 --> 00:10:55.970
So the problem is really
detecting that signal

00:10:55.970 --> 00:10:57.700
over the background signal.

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:02.140
Over the autofluorescence
of the cell.

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:06.910
And indeed, if you look
at the figure, figure one,

00:11:06.910 --> 00:11:10.900
you can very clearly see the
autofluorescence of the cell.

00:11:10.900 --> 00:11:13.550
So the fluorescence
where there's the cell

00:11:13.550 --> 00:11:16.990
is indeed much larger than
where there's no cell.

00:11:16.990 --> 00:11:21.190
The autofluorescence is, I'd
say, the primary challenge

00:11:21.190 --> 00:11:22.060
here.

00:11:22.060 --> 00:11:23.850
Of course, there are
many, many others.

00:11:23.850 --> 00:11:24.350
Right.

00:11:24.350 --> 00:11:27.300
So this is potentially
a big problem.

00:11:31.037 --> 00:11:32.620
And in order to get
around that, there

00:11:32.620 --> 00:11:35.720
are all these other
strategies that the author's

00:11:35.720 --> 00:11:36.890
going to implement.

00:11:36.890 --> 00:11:37.638
Yes?

00:11:37.638 --> 00:11:39.054
AUDIENCE: What is
the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:11:42.794 --> 00:11:43.460
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:46.170
So many things are
weakly fluorescent,

00:11:46.170 --> 00:11:47.750
I think is the short answer.

00:11:47.750 --> 00:11:51.285
And this also depends
upon, for example, cells

00:11:51.285 --> 00:11:53.660
are more autofluorescent if
you grow them in a rich media

00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:56.540
than in minimal media, for
some mysterious reason.

00:11:56.540 --> 00:11:57.190
Yeah.

00:11:57.190 --> 00:11:58.510
But it's really just that
there are many things that

00:11:58.510 --> 00:11:59.440
are weakly fluorescent.

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:01.648
And it's just there are a
lot of molecules in a cell.

00:12:04.384 --> 00:12:06.220
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:06.220 --> 00:12:09.370
PROFESSOR: Yeah, right.

00:12:09.370 --> 00:12:11.890
In the case that you put
in a fluorescent protein

00:12:11.890 --> 00:12:14.780
or a fluorescent
dye, then it has

00:12:14.780 --> 00:12:18.430
rather well-defined absorption
and emission spectra.

00:12:18.430 --> 00:12:21.020
And each individual
absorber emitter

00:12:21.020 --> 00:12:23.722
indeed has a well-defined
absorption emission profile.

00:12:23.722 --> 00:12:25.930
But then in the cell, there
are just many, many, many

00:12:25.930 --> 00:12:27.740
of them, which means
that there's rather

00:12:27.740 --> 00:12:29.970
what you want to
call an absorption

00:12:29.970 --> 00:12:32.520
of broadband emission.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:36.150
So indeed, in some wavelengths,
it's worse than in others.

00:12:36.150 --> 00:12:39.130
But it's not that you get
well-defined peaks the way

00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:42.130
you do for a single
kind of [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:42.130 --> 00:12:44.455
AUDIENCE: I guess I was
just wondering [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:47.505 --> 00:12:48.130
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:12:48.130 --> 00:12:51.300
And indeed, in this case,
they're exciting with a laser.

00:12:51.300 --> 00:12:52.900
So at least on the
excitation, it's

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:55.560
as precise as you can hope for.

00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:59.970
And indeed, on the emission
they will use a filter.

00:12:59.970 --> 00:13:01.790
So they're not going
to be absorbed.

00:13:01.790 --> 00:13:03.750
It's probably a few
tens of nanometers

00:13:03.750 --> 00:13:05.350
that they're looking at.

00:13:05.350 --> 00:13:07.100
So in that sense, they
are filtering out,

00:13:07.100 --> 00:13:08.800
but still, there is
autofluorescence.

00:13:17.134 --> 00:13:19.570
All right.

00:13:19.570 --> 00:13:26.690
Now getting at this question
of the single molecule

