00:16:56.870 --> 00:17:01.960
And this is a fundamental
physics limitation,

00:17:01.960 --> 00:17:07.790
that if you are imaging
something with light that

00:17:07.790 --> 00:17:11.210
is of some wavelength,
lambda, this

00:17:11.210 --> 00:17:14.765
is of order lambda over 2-- it
depends on numerical aperture

00:17:14.765 --> 00:17:15.890
or projective and so forth.

00:17:15.890 --> 00:17:16.940
But you know.

00:17:16.940 --> 00:17:17.990
So order of lambda.

00:17:17.990 --> 00:17:18.990
A little bit less maybe.

00:17:21.900 --> 00:17:25.800
And indeed, the
wavelength of the light

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:29.070
that's being used
here is-- they're

00:17:29.070 --> 00:17:30.780
exciting with 500 something.

00:17:30.780 --> 00:17:39.630
And then let me just-- 514.

00:17:39.630 --> 00:17:41.050
OK.

00:17:41.050 --> 00:17:44.280
So indeed, what happens
is that we shine in light.

00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:52.340
So this is the lambda
incident that is 514.

00:17:52.340 --> 00:17:56.890
Now, there's going to be some
GFP that looks like this.

00:17:56.890 --> 00:18:02.060
And then, we're going to
