00:18:27.030 --> 00:18:31.120
Now, if you just have scattering
off something-- so let's

00:18:31.120 --> 00:18:33.510
say that we had a
gold particle, and we

00:18:33.510 --> 00:18:36.290
shine-- what's going
to be the relationship

00:18:36.290 --> 00:18:38.652
between lamba incident
and lambda emission?

00:18:42.990 --> 00:18:45.610
Is it possible to have the
same wavelength come out

00:18:45.610 --> 00:18:47.965
as you put in of some object?

00:18:52.620 --> 00:18:53.120
Yes.

00:18:53.120 --> 00:18:55.800
If you just have
something, a mirror,

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:57.960
you can get back--
so it is possible.

00:18:57.960 --> 00:19:01.560
But in general, there's
going to be some dissipation.

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:03.340
It's a question of
how much and so forth.

00:19:03.340 --> 00:19:06.600
But certainly for something
like fluorescence,

00:19:06.600 --> 00:19:09.260
you have a higher
energy photon, and you

00:19:09.260 --> 00:19:10.790
have a photon that's emitted.

00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:16.090
And of course, energy
goes as 1 over lambda.

00:19:18.620 --> 00:19:23.070
Now, this is useful
because you can actually

00:19:23.070 --> 00:19:24.590
spectrally separate things.

00:19:29.815 --> 00:19:31.190
I just want to
highlight, though,

00:19:31.190 --> 00:19:34.330
that if this separation
is of order 300

00:19:34.330 --> 00:19:42.300
nanometers and our protein
is-- that [INAUDIBLE] our GFP.

00:19:42.300 --> 00:19:43.460
Nicely drawn.

00:19:43.460 --> 00:19:44.800
Not even quite to scale.

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:47.340
To scale, it's
actually even smaller.

00:19:47.340 --> 00:19:49.430
It's a factor of 100 in size.

00:19:49.430 --> 00:19:58.480
This thing is only 3 nanometers
in size, 300 nanometers wide.

00:20:03.570 --> 00:20:07.790
Now, it's important to be
clear about what this means,

00:20:07.790 --> 00:20:10.580
this diffraction limited spot.

00:20:10.580 --> 00:20:13.830
The first thing to note
is that what it means

00:20:13.830 --> 00:20:16.900
is that if you have two
proteins-- so for example,

00:20:16.900 --> 00:20:19.560
I add another one
over here-- that it's

00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:21.940
going to be very hard to
tell that we have those two

00:20:21.940 --> 00:20:24.180
proteins next to each other.

00:20:24.180 --> 00:20:25.680
Because the resulting
fluorescence

00:20:25.680 --> 00:20:29.670
pattern will look
essentially the same.

00:20:29.670 --> 00:20:32.320
Will it be exactly the same?

00:20:32.320 --> 00:20:33.920
What's going to change?

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:34.710
The intensity.

00:20:34.710 --> 00:20:37.670
The intensity, you expect
to go up by a factor of two,

00:20:37.670 --> 00:20:40.170
absent some interaction between.

00:20:40.170 --> 00:20:42.160
You can, in principle,
get interactions there.

00:20:42.160 --> 00:20:44.500
But let's for now assume
that there's no interaction.

00:20:44.500 --> 00:20:44.620
Right.

00:20:44.620 --> 00:20:47.161
Then the intensity wouldn't need
to go up by a factor of two.

00:20:47.161 --> 00:20:51.290
But unless you're very careful
about all of your optics

00:20:51.290 --> 00:20:53.000
and so forth, it's
actually a challenge

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:59.610
to use this intensity alone
to distinguish these things.

00:20:59.610 --> 00:21:02.030
It's only-- so the statement
with a diffraction--

00:21:02.030 --> 00:21:06.180
you need these two proteins
to be separated by something

00:21:06.180 --> 00:21:08.190
like lambda over
2 in order for you

00:21:08.190 --> 00:21:10.180
to start to see the separation.

00:21:10.180 --> 00:21:10.680
Right.

00:21:10.680 --> 00:21:12.870
Because then you have
something that looks like this.

00:21:12.870 --> 00:21:14.161
Something that looks like this.

00:21:14.161 --> 00:21:21.019
And then the sum of those
two, indeed-- so you say,

00:21:21.019 --> 00:21:23.560
all right, well, it looks like
there are two molecules there.

00:21:28.570 --> 00:21:33.009
Now, I just want
to-- and the notion

00:21:33.009 --> 00:21:35.300
of a lot of these so-called
super resolution techniques

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:37.120
is figuring out a way to
distinguish these things,

00:21:37.120 --> 00:21:39.328
and we'll maybe say something
about that in a moment.

00:21:39.328 --> 00:21:42.030
But I just want to highlight
that if we come back

00:21:42.030 --> 00:21:46.360
to the situation where we
have a single protein there.

00:21:46.360 --> 00:21:52.240
Now the question is,
how accurately can we

00:21:52.240 --> 00:21:54.750
tell where that protein
is, if we know that there's

00:21:54.750 --> 00:21:55.916
just a single protein there?

00:22:19.230 --> 00:22:22.320
Now in particular,
this size of the spot

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:30.590
is telling us something,
but it might not

00:22:30.590 --> 00:22:32.410
be quite as strong
of a limitation

00:22:32.410 --> 00:22:35.300
as it appears at first glance.

00:22:35.300 --> 00:22:38.400
And that's because in
this case, well maybe

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:42.990
I'll bring it back, what
we see is a big spot.

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:45.300
300 nanometers, kind of wide.

00:22:45.300 --> 00:22:48.450
But if we see this and we know
it's just a single protein

00:22:48.450 --> 00:22:51.440
there, I mean, could the
protein be over here?

00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:52.040
No.

00:22:52.040 --> 00:22:53.914
If the protein where
over here, then the spot

00:22:53.914 --> 00:22:58.816
would be over there right.

00:22:58.816 --> 00:23:02.000
So actually, even though
the size of the spot

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.332
is 300 nanometers,
in principle, if you

00:23:04.332 --> 00:23:05.790
want to know where
that protein is,

00:23:05.790 --> 00:23:08.327
if you know there's
just a single protein,

00:23:08.327 --> 00:23:10.160
well, in that case what
you want to know is,

00:23:10.160 --> 00:23:13.860
where's the center
of that distribution?

00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:17.040
And that problem, well, the
width of the distribution

00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:19.100
is relevant.

00:23:19.100 --> 00:23:21.910
But there's something else
that's also very relevant.

00:23:25.570 --> 00:23:30.600
And quite generally, if you
measure some quantity n times,

00:23:30.600 --> 00:23:42.960
and you want to know-- so you're
measuring the height of min

00:23:42.960 --> 00:23:48.760
entering the army-- if you
want to know the mean, what

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:54.561
is it that determines your
uncertainty around the mean?

00:23:54.561 --> 00:23:55.060
Right.

00:23:55.060 --> 00:23:57.840
There's the sample size.

00:23:57.840 --> 00:23:59.850
Now, does the width of
the distribution enter?

00:24:02.341 --> 00:24:02.840
Yeah.

00:24:02.840 --> 00:24:11.590
So in general, your
uncertainty in the mean

00:24:11.590 --> 00:24:16.070
is going to go with the width
of the distribution, sigma

00:24:16.070 --> 00:24:23.005
of whatever, divided by--
what do I put down here?

00:24:23.005 --> 00:24:27.580
Root of N, where N is the
number of samples that we take.

00:24:33.180 --> 00:24:38.490
What this is saying
is that as we sample

00:24:38.490 --> 00:24:42.210
this distribution
more and more, does

00:24:42.210 --> 00:24:47.520
the standard deviation of the
distribution, does it go to 0?

00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:48.020
No.

00:24:50.446 --> 00:24:51.820
These are all
trivial statements,

00:24:51.820 --> 00:24:53.940
but I can't tell
you how many times

00:24:53.940 --> 00:24:55.180
I see this getting confused.

00:24:55.180 --> 00:24:55.680
OK.

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:57.450
So if you measure
many, many, many times,

00:24:57.450 --> 00:25:00.260
you get a very
beautiful distribution.

00:25:00.260 --> 00:25:01.740
Right.

00:25:01.740 --> 00:25:03.570
The width of this
region of the sigma,

00:25:03.570 --> 00:25:05.805
that you get very accurately.

00:25:05.805 --> 00:25:08.744
It's true also that your
uncertainty in the width, that

00:25:08.744 --> 00:25:09.660
actually does go to 0.

00:25:09.660 --> 00:25:11.618
But the width of it, the
width doesn't go to 0.

00:25:11.618 --> 00:25:13.890
The width of the distribution.

00:25:13.890 --> 00:25:17.700
But your uncertainty in the
mean, that goes down as 1

00:25:17.700 --> 00:25:23.100
over root of N. And what is N in
the case our detection business

00:25:23.100 --> 00:25:25.650
here?

00:25:25.650 --> 00:25:26.670
The number of photons.

00:25:26.670 --> 00:25:27.170
Right?

00:25:27.170 --> 00:25:30.550
Now, of course, in
the actual experiment,

00:25:30.550 --> 00:25:32.600
we don't get precisely
this distribution.

00:25:32.600 --> 00:25:35.486
Instead, it's kind of
sort of quantized somehow

00:25:35.486 --> 00:25:36.860
spatially, because
we're actually

00:25:36.860 --> 00:25:38.840
detecting it on a CCD chip.

00:25:38.840 --> 00:25:39.340
All right.

00:25:39.340 --> 00:25:41.760
So you can go and do the
math, figure out everything.

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:43.635
But actually, that's
not as much a limitation

00:25:43.635 --> 00:25:45.220
as you might have expected.

00:25:45.220 --> 00:25:47.970
In many cases, the pixel
size on the image plane

00:25:47.970 --> 00:25:51.060
is actually something
like 100 nanometers.

00:25:51.060 --> 00:25:53.662
So this distribution
that measure,

00:25:53.662 --> 00:25:56.120
although in principle it looks
like this, what you actually

00:25:56.120 --> 00:26:00.410
measure is something that
looks like-- well, maybe I

00:26:00.410 --> 00:26:09.960
should-- something like that.

00:26:09.960 --> 00:26:10.670
Right.

00:26:10.670 --> 00:26:16.990
Because you have discrete
pixels on the CCD.

00:26:16.990 --> 00:26:20.210
And it feels that that should
just kind of totally screw you.

00:26:20.210 --> 00:26:21.800
But if you go and
do the math, you

00:26:21.800 --> 00:26:24.430
find it's not as bad
as you might expect.

00:26:24.430 --> 00:26:26.604
So broadly, you do get
essentially something

00:26:26.604 --> 00:26:28.020
that goes as 1
over the root of N,

00:26:28.020 --> 00:26:29.394
where N is the
number of photons.

00:26:29.394 --> 00:26:34.275
And if you collect 10 to the
4 photons, that actually,

00:26:34.275 --> 00:26:35.940
it's a lot of photons.

00:26:35.940 --> 00:26:38.740
So if we want to
know the uncertainty

00:26:38.740 --> 00:26:42.530
in the center of our
distribution, well, this thing,

00:26:42.530 --> 00:26:46.910
we might have something that's
of order 300 nanometers here.

00:26:46.910 --> 00:26:48.610
We take the square
root of 10 to the 4.

00:26:51.130 --> 00:26:51.630
All right.

00:26:51.630 --> 00:26:55.340
So we get to divide
by something like 100.

00:26:55.340 --> 00:26:57.330
And these are all
very rough numbers.

00:26:57.330 --> 00:27:01.180
But the point is
that we can get down

00:27:01.180 --> 00:27:05.340
to nanometer resolution in
terms of the uncertainty

00:27:05.340 --> 00:27:08.060
that which we know the
mean of that distribution.

00:27:08.060 --> 00:27:08.614
Yes?

00:27:08.614 --> 00:27:09.530
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:13.019 --> 00:27:13.935
PROFESSOR: Yeah, yeah.

00:27:13.935 --> 00:27:14.435
Right.

00:27:14.435 --> 00:27:15.940
So again, it's surprising.

00:27:15.940 --> 00:27:18.905
The thing is that
even with just two,

00:27:18.905 --> 00:27:20.530
in principle, we can
be very sensitive.

00:27:20.530 --> 00:27:21.029
Right?

00:27:21.029 --> 00:27:25.250
I mean, actually,
sometimes people actually

00:27:25.250 --> 00:27:27.580
do just put it on like
quadrant photo detector, where

00:27:27.580 --> 00:27:30.610
you really only get
essentially binary information.

00:27:30.610 --> 00:27:34.930
But even with just two, if I say
OK, well, it looks like this,

00:27:34.930 --> 00:27:37.430
or if it looks a
little bit like that,

00:27:37.430 --> 00:27:39.380
if there's no error in
our measurements there,

00:27:39.380 --> 00:27:43.120
then you can actually get
that location very well.

00:27:43.120 --> 00:27:44.950
Yeah.

00:27:44.950 --> 00:27:45.840
It's surprising.

00:27:45.840 --> 00:27:48.290
I'm not going to like.

00:27:48.290 --> 00:27:50.520
Yeah, but even with
this quantization

00:27:50.520 --> 00:27:52.607
of some sort that's
due to the CCD, city

00:27:52.607 --> 00:27:54.565
you can still get down
to nanometer resolution.

00:27:58.697 --> 00:28:01.280
Your resolution is worse than
it would be if you knew actually

00:28:01.280 --> 00:28:02.863
exactly where each
photon was hitting,

00:28:02.863 --> 00:28:06.660
but it's not very
sensitive, actually.

00:28:06.660 --> 00:28:08.400
And indeed, in the
presence of-- and

00:28:08.400 --> 00:28:09.858
this is a highly
technical comment.

00:28:09.858 --> 00:28:12.550
But in the presence of
read noise and other kinds

00:28:12.550 --> 00:28:15.050
of noise in the CCD,
actually, in many cases,

00:28:15.050 --> 00:28:17.610
it's actually better to
have somewhat larger pixels,

00:28:17.610 --> 00:28:19.960
again, than you would expect.

00:28:19.960 --> 00:28:22.432
So these balancing
many different things.

00:28:22.432 --> 00:28:24.390
People have thought
carefully about this stuff.

00:28:24.390 --> 00:28:28.780
But in the end, 100 nanometer
pixel is actually fine.

00:28:28.780 --> 00:28:33.120
And just to be clear, it's 100
nanometers at the sample plane.

00:28:33.120 --> 00:28:35.530
So it's typically
of order 10 microns

00:28:35.530 --> 00:28:38.470
size on the camera itself.

00:28:38.470 --> 00:28:44.230
So the physical size of each of
the pixels on the cameras, 10

00:28:44.230 --> 00:28:47.030
microns within a factor
of 2, between 5 and 20,

00:28:47.030 --> 00:28:49.840
but then you get 100x
typically magnification

00:28:49.840 --> 00:28:52.620
at the sample point.

00:28:52.620 --> 00:28:55.510
So to be clear, 10
microns divided by 100

00:28:55.510 --> 00:28:58.770
is 100 nanometers.

