The key thing--
three, you can ignore.

00:29:05.710 --> 00:29:07.940
But the key thing
to notice here is

00:29:07.940 --> 00:29:10.370
this thing that's here, which
is nanometer resolution.

00:29:14.980 --> 00:29:19.510
And it's been known for decades
that this is, in principle,

00:29:19.510 --> 00:29:20.890
possible and so forth.

00:29:20.890 --> 00:29:23.790
But I think that within the
realm of single molecule

00:29:23.790 --> 00:29:30.370
biophysics, it was really
popularized in some very nice

00:29:30.370 --> 00:29:37.060
papers by Ahmet Yildiz,
et al, where they attached

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:41.240
single molecules onto the
heads of various motors

00:29:41.240 --> 00:29:44.100
as they were walking
along tracks, and showing

00:29:44.100 --> 00:29:46.190
that these motors were
walking kind of like this,

00:29:46.190 --> 00:29:47.990
by catching fluorophores here,
and then you could really just

00:29:47.990 --> 00:29:49.460
see it, see them walking it.

00:29:54.490 --> 00:29:56.460
Any questions about
why it's in principle

00:29:56.460 --> 00:30:00.536
possible to get nanometer
resolution in this process?

00:30:00.536 --> 00:30:02.464
AUDIENCE: Doesn't this
assume that the protein

00:30:02.464 --> 00:30:04.874
is 100% static?

00:30:04.874 --> 00:30:05.838
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:30:05.838 --> 00:30:06.754
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:11.064 --> 00:30:11.730
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:30:11.730 --> 00:30:12.480
Yeah, indeed.

00:30:12.480 --> 00:30:15.360
Right now, I'm assuming
that this thing is constant.

00:30:15.360 --> 00:30:19.330
And the question is like, how
much movement is a problem?

00:30:19.330 --> 00:30:21.626
And so then you
have to-- you know.

00:30:21.626 --> 00:30:22.542
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:25.360 --> 00:30:26.360
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:30.210
So indeed, often, you're
trading off spatial resolution

00:30:30.210 --> 00:30:31.690
for temporal resolution.

00:30:31.690 --> 00:30:34.455
And also, the intensity of
your laser, and so forth.

00:30:34.455 --> 00:30:35.830
But in these sort
of experiments,

00:30:35.830 --> 00:30:39.120
I think that what they
did is they slowed down

00:30:39.120 --> 00:30:40.910
the motors quite a lot.

00:30:40.910 --> 00:30:42.410
So it was limiting ATP.

00:30:42.410 --> 00:30:44.260
So indeed, the motors
in those experiments,

00:30:44.260 --> 00:30:48.340
I think they were taking
steps of order every second

00:30:48.340 --> 00:30:48.990
or 10 seconds.

00:30:48.990 --> 00:30:52.080
I mean, it was as slow as
you can go, and still, yes.

00:30:52.080 --> 00:30:53.530
And then at each
location, I think

00:30:53.530 --> 00:30:56.175
they were collecting 10 to the
4 or a few 10 to the 4 photons.

00:30:59.310 --> 00:31:01.080
And incidentally
in this case, these

00:31:01.080 --> 00:31:02.850
are the photons that
are being collected.

00:31:02.850 --> 00:31:05.100
And typically, you
would only be collecting

00:31:05.100 --> 00:31:07.820
10%, 15% of the photons.

00:31:07.820 --> 00:31:11.380
Because the photons are actually
being emitted everywhere.

00:31:11.380 --> 00:31:14.180
But you only collect the ones
that go back to your objective.

00:31:20.680 --> 00:31:21.750
All right.

00:31:21.750 --> 00:31:24.710
I just want to make one comment
about the super resolution

00:31:24.710 --> 00:31:27.500
techniques that
have been spreading.

00:31:27.500 --> 00:31:29.000
So the question
here is, well, let's

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.804
say that you have two
proteins next to each other.

00:31:31.804 --> 00:31:32.470
What can you do?

00:31:35.110 --> 00:31:39.610
Now, the basic idea of all these
super resolution techniques

00:31:39.610 --> 00:31:45.200
is that if we know that we have
a signal for only one protein,

00:31:45.200 --> 00:31:47.120
then we can actually
figure out where it is.

00:31:47.120 --> 00:31:48.619
So what you need
to do is figure out

00:31:48.619 --> 00:31:51.595
a way so you just have
one at a time emitting.

00:31:51.595 --> 00:31:53.220
So there are various
schemes to make it

00:31:53.220 --> 00:31:57.690
so that these proteins
can either turn on or off.

00:31:57.690 --> 00:32:00.774
Now, what you can do is
if just one turns on,

00:32:00.774 --> 00:32:02.690
you got some photons,
you say OK, this protein

00:32:02.690 --> 00:32:04.610
goes over here.

00:32:04.610 --> 00:32:08.970
Then if later, this other
protein becomes fluorescent,

00:32:08.970 --> 00:32:11.090
now you can figure
out where that is.

00:32:11.090 --> 00:32:14.860
And so you do this basic
super resolution localization

00:32:14.860 --> 00:32:18.110
multiple times, and then you
can identify where things are.

00:32:21.740 --> 00:32:22.240
Yeah.

00:32:22.240 --> 00:32:25.170
So all the microscopy
guys really

00:32:25.170 --> 00:32:30.960
like to have fun acronyms.

00:32:30.960 --> 00:32:38.735
So these guys, when they did
it, they called it FIONA.

00:32:41.990 --> 00:32:43.900
So this is-- is it DreamWorks?

00:32:43.900 --> 00:32:48.290
Or this is where the green
ogre like that and then

00:32:48.290 --> 00:32:49.350
the red head?

00:32:49.350 --> 00:32:50.190
AUDIENCE: Shrek.

00:32:50.190 --> 00:32:50.620
PROFESSOR: Shrek?

00:32:50.620 --> 00:32:50.950
All right.

00:32:50.950 --> 00:32:51.460
So Shrek.

00:32:51.460 --> 00:32:53.710
And so Fiona was the redhead.

00:32:53.710 --> 00:32:55.960
And this stands for
fluorescent imaging

00:32:55.960 --> 00:32:57.410
with 1 nanometer accuracy.

00:32:59.930 --> 00:33:04.610
And then indeed, a
group at UCSF then

00:33:04.610 --> 00:33:08.910
developed SHREK, which is
simultaneous high resolution

00:33:08.910 --> 00:33:10.610
imaging-- something.

00:33:10.610 --> 00:33:11.110
OK.

00:33:11.110 --> 00:33:12.360
I can't remember how it ended.

00:33:12.360 --> 00:33:14.210
But, yeah.

00:33:14.210 --> 00:33:16.170
So the super
resolution techniques,

00:33:16.170 --> 00:33:21.150
they call them-- so Xiaowei
Zhuang at Harvard called

00:33:21.150 --> 00:33:26.050
hers STORM, stochastic
reconstruction

00:33:26.050 --> 00:33:28.270
of something or another.

00:33:28.270 --> 00:33:30.860
So this is the Zhuang method.

00:33:30.860 --> 00:33:34.150
And then Eric Betzig
called his PALM, which

00:33:34.150 --> 00:33:36.230
stood still for something else.

00:33:36.230 --> 00:33:36.820
I don't know.

00:33:36.820 --> 00:33:40.570
But in particular,
Betzig-- there's

00:33:40.570 --> 00:33:43.840
a long history of the
hard core microscopists,

00:33:43.840 --> 00:33:48.695
somehow like, developing their
techniques in their garages.

00:33:48.695 --> 00:33:50.320
I don't know what it
is, but there have

00:33:50.320 --> 00:33:51.550
been a number of these cases.

00:33:51.550 --> 00:33:53.450
And Betzig I think
was one of them.

00:33:53.450 --> 00:33:56.620
Now he's at Janelia
Farm, HHMI, and has

00:33:56.620 --> 00:34:00.264
been developing all sorts of
advanced microscopy techniques.

00:34:00.264 --> 00:34:01.930
So I think that that
[INAUDIBLE] did not

00:34:01.930 --> 00:34:03.930
develop hers in the garage.

00:34:03.930 --> 00:34:04.490
But um--

00:34:04.490 --> 00:34:07.050
AUDIENCE: And they're all
based on the same principle--

00:34:07.050 --> 00:34:07.900
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:34:07.900 --> 00:34:09.870
It's all about temporal.

00:34:09.870 --> 00:34:12.780
It's a question of
how you're getting

00:34:12.780 --> 00:34:16.150
them to turn on and off.

00:34:16.150 --> 00:34:18.610
AUDIENCE: It sounds like
[INAUDIBLE] acronyms.

00:34:18.610 --> 00:34:20.041
PROFESSOR: Oh do they also have?

00:34:20.041 --> 00:34:21.250
AUDIENCE: ROSY, COZY, NOSY.

00:34:21.250 --> 00:34:22.089
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:34:22.089 --> 00:34:22.630
Right, right.

00:34:22.630 --> 00:34:24.338
For the different
sequences or something?

00:34:24.338 --> 00:34:25.141
Yeah, yeah.

00:34:28.300 --> 00:34:33.639
All of these acronyms,
maybe I just never came up

00:34:33.639 --> 00:34:36.490
with a good one, so then I--

00:34:36.490 --> 00:34:38.880
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:38.880 --> 00:34:39.820
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:34:39.820 --> 00:34:40.870
Indeed.

00:34:40.870 --> 00:34:43.610
I always like when somebody
uses acronyms that I don't know,

00:34:43.610 --> 00:34:47.761
I always like to say, oh,
all these TLAs are tricky,

00:34:47.761 --> 00:34:48.260
or whatever.

00:34:48.260 --> 00:34:52.002
And then I say, it's
three letter acronym.

00:34:52.002 --> 00:34:53.480
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHING]

00:34:53.480 --> 00:34:55.830
PROFESSOR: I very much like
self-referential humor.

00:34:58.980 --> 00:35:00.420
OK.

00:35:00.420 --> 00:35:02.670
So that's the idea of the
super resolution techniques.

00:35:06.924 --> 00:35:08.340
Any questions about
that before we

00:35:08.340 --> 00:35:10.140
kind of get back
actually to the paper?

00:35:13.530 --> 00:35:14.660
OK.

00:35:14.660 --> 00:35:17.140
Now in this whole discussion,
as was pointed out,

00:35:17.140 --> 00:35:20.950
we've been assuming that the
protein is not moving around

00:35:20.950 --> 00:35:23.430
during our imaging time.

00:35:23.430 --> 00:35:26.120
So one of the major challenges
of doing this whole business

00:35:26.120 --> 00:35:28.410
in live cells is
not only is there

00:35:28.410 --> 00:35:33.230
a lot of autofluorescence,
but in addition, you

00:35:33.230 --> 00:35:35.970
can't necessarily
wait 10 seconds

00:35:35.970 --> 00:35:39.190
to localize where this thing
is, because it will have

00:35:39.190 --> 00:35:41.180
moved somewhere else right.

00:35:41.180 --> 00:35:46.250
And in particular,
diffusion is a problem.

00:35:46.250 --> 00:35:50.272
Can somebody remind
us what the authors

00:35:50.272 --> 00:35:52.355
did in order to get around
the diffusion problems?

00:35:55.700 --> 00:35:56.902
I'm sorry what was it?

00:35:56.902 --> 00:35:58.600
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:58.600 --> 00:36:00.640
PROFESSOR: They attached
it to the membrane.

00:36:00.640 --> 00:36:01.950
And why does that help?

00:36:06.207 --> 00:36:08.854
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:08.854 --> 00:36:09.520
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:36:09.520 --> 00:36:10.920
That's perfect.

00:36:10.920 --> 00:36:12.270
Proteins diffuse slower.

00:36:12.270 --> 00:36:13.877
And I think depending
on the organism,

00:36:13.877 --> 00:36:15.960
there's more or less
diffusion and so forth right.

00:36:15.960 --> 00:36:25.500
But what they did is they
anchored to the membrane

00:36:25.500 --> 00:36:26.960
to reduce diffusion.

00:36:26.960 --> 00:36:28.418
I'll just say it
reduces diffusion.

00:36:34.330 --> 00:36:36.969
And indeed, just from a back
of the envelope calculation,

00:36:36.969 --> 00:36:38.760
you can convince yourself
that you probably

00:36:38.760 --> 00:36:41.770
are going to need to do this.

00:36:41.770 --> 00:36:45.160
So in particular, let's
ask-- in this paper,

00:36:45.160 --> 00:36:50.390
actually, they image the
fluorophore for 0.1 seconds,

00:36:50.390 --> 00:36:52.610
right?

00:36:52.610 --> 00:36:53.790
Does that sound right?

00:36:53.790 --> 00:37:05.340
So the image collected, so
delta t is equal to 0.1 sets.

00:37:05.340 --> 00:37:07.870
So the question is, how far
will a protein typically

00:37:07.870 --> 00:37:09.590
diffuse in 0.1 seconds?

00:37:13.120 --> 00:37:16.620
Well, this is why we have
diffusion calculations.

00:37:16.620 --> 00:37:18.630
Right.

00:37:18.630 --> 00:37:23.020
First of all, the
diffusion coefficient,

00:37:23.020 --> 00:37:26.210
we're going to talk more about
diffusion in a few weeks.

00:37:26.210 --> 00:37:30.077
But you should also
in principal be

00:37:30.077 --> 00:37:31.660
able to calculate
how these things go.

00:37:31.660 --> 00:37:33.750
So in general,
this is going to be

00:37:33.750 --> 00:37:39.860
a kT over some gamma, which
tells us how hard-- so kT is

00:37:39.860 --> 00:37:40.791
thermal energy.

00:37:40.791 --> 00:37:41.290
OK.

00:37:44.660 --> 00:37:45.940
So, thermal.

00:37:45.940 --> 00:37:50.530
And at room temperature
kT is around 4.1

00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:53.095
piconewton nanometers
in some unit.

00:37:53.095 --> 00:37:55.435
There are many different
ways you can write that.

00:37:55.435 --> 00:38:00.730
Whereas gamma tells us just how
hard it is to push something.

00:38:00.730 --> 00:38:05.370
In particular, if you
push them with some force,

00:38:05.370 --> 00:38:08.650
it will move with some velocity.

00:38:08.650 --> 00:38:13.040
Now is this consistent
with freshman mechanics?

00:38:17.390 --> 00:38:17.940
No.

00:38:17.940 --> 00:38:18.640
It's not.

00:38:18.640 --> 00:38:19.140
OK.

00:38:21.975 --> 00:38:22.725
Is that a problem?

00:38:26.160 --> 00:38:28.080
So why is it that
I'm writing this?

00:38:30.555 --> 00:38:32.554
AUDIENCE: Solvents exerting
a force [INAUDIBLE]?

00:38:32.554 --> 00:38:33.262
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:38:33.262 --> 00:38:35.630
So solvents exerting a force.

00:38:35.630 --> 00:38:36.600
That's true.

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:39.970
But in the case of
freshman mechanics,

00:38:39.970 --> 00:38:43.100
when we're pushing
blocks, it's also true

00:38:43.100 --> 00:38:45.050
that the other things
are exerting forces.

00:38:45.050 --> 00:38:45.780
The tables.

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:49.210
But we still write
down F is equal to MA.

00:38:49.210 --> 00:38:52.365
So it's not just that other
things are exerting forces.

00:38:52.365 --> 00:38:53.335
Yeah?

00:38:53.335 --> 00:38:57.101
AUDIENCE: They're
always in a continuum?

00:38:57.101 --> 00:38:58.476
PROFESSOR: Always
in a continuum.

00:38:58.476 --> 00:39:01.380
AUDIENCE: They're always
surrounded by [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:01.380 --> 00:39:02.160
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:39:02.160 --> 00:39:03.130
Yeah.

00:39:03.130 --> 00:39:06.020
It's always surrounded--
but I'm actually

00:39:06.020 --> 00:39:07.290
surrounded by fluid now too.

00:39:07.290 --> 00:39:10.364
You know, you can wave
your arms and feel it.

00:39:10.364 --> 00:39:11.280
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:11.280 --> 00:39:12.155
PROFESSOR: OK, right.

00:39:12.155 --> 00:39:13.790
So it comes down
to the viscosity.

00:39:13.790 --> 00:39:16.890
Indeed, this whole thing about
being a low Reynolds number,

00:39:16.890 --> 00:39:19.690
we're going to talk about
this in much more detail

00:39:19.690 --> 00:39:22.880
in a few weeks, when we think
about how bacteria swim,

00:39:22.880 --> 00:39:23.740
and so forth.

00:39:23.740 --> 00:39:25.280
But I just want to
mention that this

00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:27.780
is because we're at this
low Reynolds number, where

00:39:27.780 --> 00:39:33.020
the so-called inertial forces,
like momentum are negligible.

00:39:33.020 --> 00:39:34.370
Inertia forces are negligible.

00:39:34.370 --> 00:39:36.470
So then it's really,
this is in some ways

00:39:36.470 --> 00:39:40.090
more like Aristotelian
physics, but it ends up

00:39:40.090 --> 00:39:43.800
being true for small
objects in viscous liquids.

00:39:46.330 --> 00:39:50.100
And indeed, this thing
it scales as the radius.

00:39:50.100 --> 00:39:56.780
So in principle, we can
actually calculate roughly

00:39:56.780 --> 00:39:59.054
how the diffusion coefficient
is going to behave

00:39:59.054 --> 00:39:59.970
as a function of size.

00:39:59.970 --> 00:40:00.990
The object and so forth.

00:40:00.990 --> 00:40:05.270
But I'll just tell you that
for a protein size object

00:40:05.270 --> 00:40:07.550
in the cell, you
might get something

00:40:07.550 --> 00:40:11.920
like 10 micron
squared per second.

00:40:14.570 --> 00:40:19.590
Now, already just
from units, you

00:40:19.590 --> 00:40:22.180
can see how the kind of
typical diffusion distance

00:40:22.180 --> 00:40:24.800
has to scale with time.

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:26.800
And in particular,
you're going to get

00:40:26.800 --> 00:40:29.700
that the typical
kind of distance

00:40:29.700 --> 00:40:35.590
that you go in a
typical distance-- we'll

00:40:35.590 --> 00:40:38.570
say square root, because it's
the square root of 2 times D

00:40:38.570 --> 00:40:40.450
times time.

00:40:40.450 --> 00:40:44.272
So you can see if you
multiply the time by the D,

00:40:44.272 --> 00:40:45.880
then you end up with
a micron squared,

00:40:45.880 --> 00:40:48.475
so you have to take a square
root to get something that's

00:40:48.475 --> 00:40:51.320
a characteristic distance.

00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:54.450
And indeed, this is the
kind of math that I can do.

00:40:54.450 --> 00:40:58.230
So this is an order one micron.

00:41:03.160 --> 00:41:06.483
And how big is an E. coli cell?

00:41:06.483 --> 00:41:07.780
AUDIENCE: One micron?

00:41:07.780 --> 00:41:09.450
PROFESSOR: One micron,
roughly, right?

00:41:09.450 --> 00:41:11.860
So it might be a
couple microns long.

00:41:11.860 --> 00:41:13.400
A bit less than a
micron in width.

00:41:13.400 --> 00:41:15.842
And what this is saying
is that 0.1 seconds, which

00:41:15.842 --> 00:41:17.300
is our exposure
time on our camera,

00:41:17.300 --> 00:41:19.660
you would expect
something like GFP

00:41:19.660 --> 00:41:22.550
to diffuse around
roughly the cell volume.

00:41:22.550 --> 00:41:24.951
And maybe not the entire one,
but a fair fraction of it.

00:41:24.951 --> 00:41:26.950
What this is saying is
that the diffusion really

00:41:26.950 --> 00:41:30.114
would be a problem, even with
this relatively short exposure

00:41:30.114 --> 00:41:30.614
time.

00:41:30.614 --> 00:41:31.916
Yeah?

00:41:31.916 --> 00:41:32.833
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:41:32.833 --> 00:41:33.457
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:41:33.457 --> 00:41:35.424
So this is assuming
that the cytoplasm has

00:41:35.424 --> 00:41:37.340
a viscosity that's maybe
an order of magnitude

00:41:37.340 --> 00:41:38.380
larger than water.

00:41:38.380 --> 00:41:40.030
And that's just
because the inside

00:41:40.030 --> 00:41:42.510
is chock full of
proteins and so forth.

00:41:42.510 --> 00:41:45.050
Now, there's a lot
of discussion of what

00:41:45.050 --> 00:41:49.170
the mechanism is of diffusion
and transport inside cells.

00:41:49.170 --> 00:41:50.630
It may depend on the size.

00:41:50.630 --> 00:41:52.420
It's a very complicated area.

00:41:52.420 --> 00:41:55.171
But for our purposes,
this is a reasonable way

00:41:55.171 --> 00:41:55.920
to think about it.

00:41:55.920 --> 00:41:58.270
But indeed, the viscosity
of the cytoplasm, you'd

00:41:58.270 --> 00:42:00.900
expect to be significantly more
than the viscosity of water.

00:42:03.760 --> 00:42:04.563
Yeah?

00:42:04.563 --> 00:42:08.270
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
lower the [INAUDIBLE] time?

00:42:08.270 --> 00:42:09.475
PROFESSOR: Lower the?

00:42:09.475 --> 00:42:10.100
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:42:10.100 --> 00:42:11.982
Like two orders of
magnitude instead of one?

00:42:11.982 --> 00:42:12.690
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:42:12.690 --> 00:42:15.390
So in principle, we could.

00:42:15.390 --> 00:42:17.610
