00:58:56.006 --> 00:58:57.630
Because this plot
here is really a plot

00:58:57.630 --> 00:59:00.285
of the fraction of
the molecules that

00:59:00.285 --> 00:59:02.380
have survived as a
function of time.

00:59:02.380 --> 00:59:03.510
Right.

00:59:03.510 --> 00:59:07.400
So indeed, the
probability of survival

00:59:07.400 --> 00:59:10.660
for an exponential process like
this is a function of time, t,

00:59:10.660 --> 00:59:15.610
is going to be equal
to e to the minus t

00:59:15.610 --> 00:59:17.700
over some constant [INAUDIBLE].

00:59:20.720 --> 00:59:22.780
And what is t in tau?

00:59:22.780 --> 00:59:27.630
Well, t is this
time 1.2 seconds.

00:59:30.660 --> 00:59:34.610
So we have e to the-- we'll
write it like an exponent.

00:59:34.610 --> 00:59:35.720
So now we have a minus.

00:59:35.720 --> 00:59:41.060
We have 1.2 seconds divided by
the lifetime in this condition,

00:59:41.060 --> 00:59:42.840
we're told is 250 milliseconds.

00:59:42.840 --> 00:59:49.880
So we can write 0.25 seconds.

00:59:49.880 --> 00:59:56.150
So this is approximately
e to the minus 5,

00:59:56.150 --> 00:59:59.715
which indeed, is equal to
what I thought is 0.8%.

01:00:02.850 --> 01:00:09.240
So it's around 1%,

01:00:09.240 --> 01:00:12.670
Are there any questions about
this logic or this calculation?

01:00:12.670 --> 01:00:15.036
Yes?

01:00:15.036 --> 01:00:15.952
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:20.300 --> 01:00:21.349
PROFESSOR: Oh, no, no.

01:00:21.349 --> 01:00:21.890
Sorry, sorry.

01:00:21.890 --> 01:00:22.640
No, no.

01:00:22.640 --> 01:00:29.200
Bleaching, this is a result
of chemical inactivation

01:00:29.200 --> 01:00:32.210
of the fluorescent protein
that is kind of induced

01:00:32.210 --> 01:00:35.900
by being in this excited state.

01:00:35.900 --> 01:00:38.460
So the idea is that if
you're shining light

01:00:38.460 --> 01:00:40.800
on this fluorescent
protein, then

01:00:40.800 --> 01:00:48.160
it's going to bleach at a rate
that is kind of-- distribution

01:00:48.160 --> 01:00:51.920
of say, lifetime's going to
be exponential with a time

01:00:51.920 --> 01:00:53.430
constant of 250 milliseconds.

01:00:53.430 --> 01:00:54.346
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:57.301 --> 01:00:58.300
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:00:58.300 --> 01:00:58.890
That's right.

01:00:58.890 --> 01:01:00.890
But it's a one-step
process though.

01:01:00.890 --> 01:01:01.890
That's what we see here.

01:01:01.890 --> 01:01:04.160
It's not that that
individual protein

01:01:04.160 --> 01:01:06.960
is getting worse and
worse as it's being used.

01:01:06.960 --> 01:01:09.890
But it's really just
that there's some rate

01:01:09.890 --> 01:01:11.590
that it-- some
probability, of course,

01:01:11.590 --> 01:01:15.701
time that it cycles that it is,
we'll say for now, irreversibly

01:01:15.701 --> 01:01:16.200
inactivated.

01:01:19.460 --> 01:01:22.620
There are also all these
so-called blinking events,

01:01:22.620 --> 01:01:27.360
where fluorescent molecules
can kind of temporarily

01:01:27.360 --> 01:01:30.065
go into a non-fluorescent
state, and then they return,

01:01:30.065 --> 01:01:33.620
but right now, we're talking
about these irreversible steps.

01:01:36.890 --> 01:01:39.830
Are there any other questions
about what I mean by bleaching,

01:01:39.830 --> 01:01:41.570
or this calculation?

01:01:47.054 --> 01:01:48.320
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:48.320 --> 01:01:52.300
PROFESSOR: So my claim
is that 0.8% is very

01:01:52.300 --> 01:01:54.264
close, is approximately 1%.

01:01:54.264 --> 01:01:55.180
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:58.150 --> 01:02:01.240
PROFESSOR: Yes, sorry.

01:02:01.240 --> 01:02:03.025
I did something funny here.

01:02:03.025 --> 01:02:03.525
Yeah, yeah.

01:02:09.950 --> 01:02:12.989
So it's useful to just kind of
go through these calculations.

01:02:12.989 --> 01:02:15.030
And actually, I think that
in going through them,

01:02:15.030 --> 01:02:16.820
you kind of really get
to get a sense of why

01:02:16.820 --> 01:02:18.736
they design their
experiments the way they did

01:02:18.736 --> 01:02:20.080
and everything.

01:02:20.080 --> 01:02:25.000
So the idea is that what they're
doing here every three minutes,

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:27.890
they're looking at the
cells, and they're asking,

01:02:27.890 --> 01:02:31.160
is there are a protein, or
maybe more than one here?

01:02:31.160 --> 01:02:35.910
And then they try to kill all
those fluorescent proteins.

01:02:35.910 --> 01:02:39.170
And then they look again
three minutes later.

01:02:39.170 --> 01:02:43.210
Are there any new
proteins that were made.

01:02:43.210 --> 01:02:43.860
Yes?

01:02:43.860 --> 01:02:45.979
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:02:45.979 --> 01:02:49.230
You can't see it [INAUDIBLE].

01:02:49.230 --> 01:02:50.230
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:02:50.230 --> 01:02:50.730
You don't--

01:02:50.730 --> 01:02:52.944
AUDIENCE: Do you calibrate
the intensity [INAUDIBLE].

01:02:52.944 --> 01:02:55.360
PROFESSOR: So what they're
really doing is they're asking,

01:02:55.360 --> 01:02:57.140
how many spots do I see?

01:03:00.600 --> 01:03:02.340
So in that experiment,
they don't know

01:03:02.340 --> 01:03:05.330
that it was a single molecule.

01:03:05.330 --> 01:03:06.700
Although I think that in many--

01:03:06.700 --> 01:03:11.111
AUDIENCE: Then why do they
talk about this [INAUDIBLE]?

01:03:11.111 --> 01:03:13.110
PROFESSOR: Well, that's
how they checked to make

01:03:13.110 --> 01:03:14.437
sure it was a single molecule.

01:03:14.437 --> 01:03:16.520
Although I think that
actually, in principle here,

01:03:16.520 --> 01:03:20.310
I think they actually maybe
do continue to look at them.

01:03:20.310 --> 01:03:21.727
That's not part
of their analysis.

01:03:21.727 --> 01:03:23.310
So for many of the
case, they actually

01:03:23.310 --> 01:03:25.800
do see that this molecule is
here, and then it bleaches,

01:03:25.800 --> 01:03:28.590
and a different molecule
was here, and it bleached.

01:03:31.120 --> 01:03:34.110
But what they're really
asking is at the beginning,

01:03:34.110 --> 01:03:37.654
how many fluorescent
proteins did I see?

01:03:37.654 --> 01:03:40.070
And I think the camera actually
maybe was collecting still

01:03:40.070 --> 01:03:41.195
during that bleaching step.

01:03:41.195 --> 01:03:43.050
It's just that it wasn't
kind of part of it.

01:03:43.050 --> 01:03:46.624
Their analysis is in some ways
really just based on this.

01:03:46.624 --> 01:03:48.290
Or in other experiments,
you can go look

01:03:48.290 --> 01:03:51.155
to confirm that it
bleaches single step here.

01:03:55.610 --> 01:03:56.580
OK.

01:03:56.580 --> 01:03:59.320
So we spent a long time talking
like the general idea of how

01:03:59.320 --> 01:04:02.680
to design these
experiments and so forth.

01:04:02.680 --> 01:04:04.900
I'm not going to say very
much about the design

01:04:04.900 --> 01:04:09.560
of the experiments, except
that they did a number things.

01:04:09.560 --> 01:04:11.640
They used this
Venus protein that

01:04:11.640 --> 01:04:17.320
has a faster maturation
than traditional GFP.

01:04:17.320 --> 01:04:20.610
They also targeted
it to the membrane,

01:04:20.610 --> 01:04:23.500
not by putting Venus
into the membrane-- that

01:04:23.500 --> 01:04:25.920
would be tricky, I
think-- but rather

01:04:25.920 --> 01:04:30.560
by attaching the Venus protein
to another protein that

01:04:30.560 --> 01:04:32.080
is put in the membrane.

01:04:32.080 --> 01:04:34.124
And indeed, this TSR
membrane protein,

01:04:34.124 --> 01:04:35.540
we're going to be
talking about it

01:04:35.540 --> 01:04:37.600
in a couple of weeks
when we're discussing

01:04:37.600 --> 01:04:41.660
the chemotaxis network that is
in E. coli for how E. coli find

01:04:41.660 --> 01:04:44.030
food and so forth.

01:04:44.030 --> 01:04:46.820
I think that in reading these
papers, it's interesting.

01:04:46.820 --> 01:04:49.720
Sometimes, authors make
kind of a side comment

01:04:49.720 --> 01:04:52.775
that just illuminates kind of
how difficult everything was.

01:04:52.775 --> 01:04:54.650
And I think that they
had a nice one in here,

01:04:54.650 --> 01:04:58.560
where they said that they were
checking with TSR to make sure

01:04:58.560 --> 01:05:04.130
that the behavior of the
TSR Venus and just Venus

01:05:04.130 --> 01:05:06.670
were similar in terms of
the amount of fluorescence.

01:05:06.670 --> 01:05:09.120
And then, they say,
no notable difference

01:05:09.120 --> 01:05:11.810
was observed, indicating that
the introduction of the TSR

01:05:11.810 --> 01:05:15.890
sequence does not change the
yield of Venus production,

01:05:15.890 --> 01:05:18.560
which is not the case for
many other membrane targeting

01:05:18.560 --> 01:05:20.060
sequences that we tested.

01:05:20.060 --> 01:05:23.020
So this is like, a little
add-on onto the sentence

01:05:23.020 --> 01:05:27.480
that is like, I mean, six
months of somebody's life

01:05:27.480 --> 01:05:29.870
was dedicated to
trying-- you can just

01:05:29.870 --> 01:05:33.190
imagine all the over
coffee, their frustration.

01:05:33.190 --> 01:05:34.940
They tried all of
these different things,

01:05:34.940 --> 01:05:39.100
and they always got-- and for
an awful lot of these things,

01:05:39.100 --> 01:05:42.860
I would have still been very
much interested in the study,

01:05:42.860 --> 01:05:48.092
even if the addition of TSR
did change the kinetics.

01:05:48.092 --> 01:05:50.050
Because I think that
still is very interesting.

01:05:50.050 --> 01:05:52.890
But they really wanted
this to be just airtight,

01:05:52.890 --> 01:05:55.030
or maybe the referees
need to be-- I don't know.

01:05:55.030 --> 01:05:57.238
But you can tell that they
just went to a lot of work

01:05:57.238 --> 01:06:01.550
to try to find the thing where
everything would be just right.

01:06:06.560 --> 01:06:10.610
Now, once they kind of
described their setup,

01:06:10.610 --> 01:06:15.020
they had this wonderful
paragraph, I think.

01:06:15.020 --> 01:06:17.900
They say, oh, these proteins,
they're generating bursts,

01:06:17.900 --> 01:06:19.945
and the number in
the bursts varies,

01:06:19.945 --> 01:06:21.320
and there's spread,
and so forth.

01:06:21.320 --> 01:06:24.740
And they very nicely
tell us, with this data,

01:06:24.740 --> 01:06:27.510
we can ask four questions.

01:06:27.510 --> 01:06:29.700
And they say, do these
gene expression bursts

01:06:29.700 --> 01:06:31.135
occur randomly in time?

01:06:31.135 --> 01:06:33.030
That's going to be yes.

01:06:33.030 --> 01:06:35.730
How many mRNA new molecules
are responsible for each gene

01:06:35.730 --> 01:06:38.620
expression burst under
the repressed conditions?

01:06:38.620 --> 01:06:40.050
One.

01:06:40.050 --> 01:06:42.570
What is the distribution of
the number of protein molecules

01:06:42.570 --> 01:06:43.620
in each burst?

01:06:43.620 --> 01:06:46.710
It's going to be
geometrically distributed.

01:06:46.710 --> 01:06:48.890
And what is the origin
of the temporal spread

01:06:48.890 --> 01:06:50.760
of the individual bursts?

01:06:50.760 --> 01:06:52.489
And now, I think
that this is nice,

01:06:52.489 --> 01:06:54.030
just to give a reader
a kind of like,

01:06:54.030 --> 01:06:57.200
heads up of where we're heading.

01:06:57.200 --> 01:06:59.690
And the origin of
the temporal spread

01:06:59.690 --> 01:07:02.960
is actually-- they're arguing
is actually the Venus maturation

01:07:02.960 --> 01:07:04.030
time.

01:07:04.030 --> 01:07:06.940
So in that case, the
fact that there's

01:07:06.940 --> 01:07:09.000
a finite time for
maturation of the Venus

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:10.810
ends up allowing them
to measure the bursts

01:07:10.810 --> 01:07:12.340
in an interesting way.

01:07:12.340 --> 01:07:14.520
Before we get into
the details of that,

01:07:14.520 --> 01:07:19.680
though, I want to make sure
that we're all clear about what

01:07:19.680 --> 01:07:22.270
they mean by a burst.

01:07:22.270 --> 01:07:25.450
Because this is
something that is oddly--

01:07:25.450 --> 01:07:29.690
it feels like it's the most
trivial statement ever.

01:07:29.690 --> 01:07:31.970
But I think what we're going
to find is that there's

01:07:31.970 --> 01:07:34.672
a lot of confusion about it.

01:07:34.672 --> 01:07:36.255
This is a question,
how is it that you

01:07:36.255 --> 01:07:39.360
go from the data to the
quantities that they plot

01:07:39.360 --> 01:07:41.070
and that they're interested in?

01:07:41.070 --> 01:07:44.210
We want to get a sense of
how many proteins are made

01:07:44.210 --> 01:07:46.410
in each one of these bursts?

01:07:46.410 --> 01:07:50.150
And so they have
in Figure 3B, they

01:07:50.150 --> 01:07:54.100
plot the number of protein
molecules produced.

01:07:54.100 --> 01:07:57.150
Number of proteins produced.

01:08:00.160 --> 01:08:01.425
It's a function of time.

01:08:04.280 --> 01:08:05.790
And they have these things.

01:08:05.790 --> 01:08:08.690
And This was a cell
division event.

01:08:08.690 --> 01:08:16.010
And here they say, we have 2, 4.

01:08:16.010 --> 01:08:22.439
And here at 25 minutes,
we have this thing here,

01:08:22.439 --> 01:08:23.410
and it looks like.

01:08:30.344 --> 01:08:31.510
And then this thing goes on.

01:08:31.510 --> 01:08:41.109
And there's 50, we have
another, and so forth.

01:08:41.109 --> 01:08:46.930
This is a zoom in of
Figure 3B, the top panel.

01:08:46.930 --> 01:08:51.880
So what I want to know is, what
is the size of the first burst?

01:09:24.279 --> 01:09:27.500
So you can either look at my
beautifully drawn illustration,

01:09:27.500 --> 01:09:29.950
or you can look at the
paper in front of you.

01:09:29.950 --> 01:09:33.170
So this is a paper analyzing
the size distribution

01:09:33.170 --> 01:09:37.960
of protein bursts
observed in living cells.

01:09:37.960 --> 01:09:38.479
Right?

01:09:38.479 --> 01:09:40.319
That's the point of this paper.

01:09:42.979 --> 01:09:45.950
Now, the question is, from
the data they're collecting,

01:09:45.950 --> 01:09:49.598
we want to know what is the
size of the protein burst?

01:09:49.598 --> 01:09:50.598
The first protein burst.

01:10:04.710 --> 01:10:08.815
Now, there's no
calculation for you to do.

01:10:08.815 --> 01:10:12.050
There's not much of one.

01:10:12.050 --> 01:10:13.820
So I'm not going to
give you maybe anymore

01:10:13.820 --> 01:10:15.357
time to figure this out.

01:10:15.357 --> 01:10:16.440
So let's see where we are.

01:10:16.440 --> 01:10:17.300
Ready?

01:10:17.300 --> 01:10:21.450
Three, two, one.

01:10:21.450 --> 01:10:22.010
All right.

01:10:22.010 --> 01:10:25.650
So we got at least a
majority of the group

01:10:25.650 --> 01:10:30.050
is saying that it's indeed 3.

01:10:32.700 --> 01:10:38.146
Now, the issue here
is that the weight

01:10:38.146 --> 01:10:40.520
of the experimental design is
working so that every three

01:10:40.520 --> 01:10:44.540
minutes, what we're
asking is, how many Venus

01:10:44.540 --> 01:10:48.840
molecules kind of folded in
that previous three minutes?

01:10:48.840 --> 01:10:51.120
And then, any of
them that there are,

01:10:51.120 --> 01:10:53.920
we count, and then we kill them.

01:10:53.920 --> 01:10:54.850
And then, the next.

01:10:54.850 --> 01:10:58.110
And indeed, what happened here
is that every three minutes,

01:10:58.110 --> 01:10:59.430
they're asking this question.

01:10:59.430 --> 01:11:01.080
No proteins.

01:11:01.080 --> 01:11:03.860
And then here, they see one.

01:11:03.860 --> 01:11:06.700
Now, that's not yet
a protein burst.

01:11:06.700 --> 01:11:09.430
That's maybe a protein verse.

01:11:09.430 --> 01:11:12.806
But it could be that we're in
the middle of a protein burst.

01:11:12.806 --> 01:11:14.680
And indeed, what we see
is that the next time

01:11:14.680 --> 01:11:18.000
point, the next three
minutes, we see, oh, actually,

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:21.370
now there's two new
proteins that were produced

01:11:21.370 --> 01:11:23.020
in that next three minutes.

01:11:23.020 --> 01:11:26.330
So indeed, this whole
thing is a protein burst.

01:11:33.820 --> 01:11:35.280
So we got 1 plus 2.

01:11:35.280 --> 01:11:38.110
So that was the calculation
I was referring to.

01:11:38.110 --> 01:11:42.430
And so what they're
plotting is the distribution

01:11:42.430 --> 01:11:45.682
of these different
protein burst sizes.

01:11:45.682 --> 01:11:47.140
Now, this is a
small protein burst.

01:11:47.140 --> 01:11:51.207
They see some that
get up to be 10, 15.

01:11:51.207 --> 01:11:53.040
And that corresponds
to some of these cases,

01:11:53.040 --> 01:11:57.510
where they see something
that looks, for example, more

01:11:57.510 --> 01:12:04.685
like-- yeah, question?

01:12:04.685 --> 01:12:05.601
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:12:08.760 --> 01:12:10.590
PROFESSOR: Yeah, right.

01:12:10.590 --> 01:12:11.910
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:12:11.910 --> 01:12:14.700
PROFESSOR: Yes, exactly.

01:12:14.700 --> 01:12:19.110
And ultimately, first
of all, the number

01:12:19.110 --> 01:12:21.550
of protein bursts
per cell cycle,

01:12:21.550 --> 01:12:27.690
per hour in these
conditions, is of order one.

01:12:27.690 --> 01:12:31.120
And then the width, the
time, of a protein burst

01:12:31.120 --> 01:12:34.820
is five, seven minutes.

01:12:34.820 --> 01:12:36.560
Something like that typically.

01:12:36.560 --> 01:12:40.850
So this gives you a sense of how
frequently they will overlap.

01:12:40.850 --> 01:12:45.280
And indeed, what you expect
from this is that 15% of them

01:12:45.280 --> 01:12:48.200
are actually that they see
as one burst might actually

01:12:48.200 --> 01:12:50.710
have been two though.

01:12:50.710 --> 01:12:56.170
It's also worth
mentioning that-- right.

01:12:56.170 --> 01:12:59.220
So what I just said is in the
model, where you know that it's

01:12:59.220 --> 01:13:03.730
always just one mRNA that is
produced each time, what they

01:13:03.730 --> 01:13:06.000
say is they think is that
the promoter is tightly

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:09.230
repressed by the Lac repressor.

01:13:09.230 --> 01:13:11.320
Ever now and then, the
Lac repressor falls off,

01:13:11.320 --> 01:13:13.580
and it's going to bind again.

01:13:13.580 --> 01:13:18.226
But some fraction of that time,
when the repressor unbinds,

01:13:18.226 --> 01:13:19.850
you get the RNA p
binding, and then you

01:13:19.850 --> 01:13:21.880
get a transcription event.

01:13:21.880 --> 01:13:23.720
And I think that in
general, it is just one

01:13:23.720 --> 01:13:25.230
mRNA that is produced there.

01:13:25.230 --> 01:13:28.510
So just a single RNA polymerase
bound, and made an mRNA.

01:13:28.510 --> 01:13:30.890
But I'm sure that some
fraction of the time, it

01:13:30.890 --> 01:13:33.290
was actually two that were
produced during that time.

01:13:33.290 --> 01:13:37.110
And those would certainly
show up as one protein burst.

01:13:37.110 --> 01:13:37.610
Right?

01:13:37.610 --> 01:13:40.620
Because the lifetime of
the mRNAs in this situation

01:13:40.620 --> 01:13:41.560
is of order what?

01:13:44.560 --> 01:13:45.060
Yeah.

01:13:45.060 --> 01:13:47.890
It was, I think, one and
a half minutes maybe?

01:13:47.890 --> 01:13:48.510
It was short.

01:13:51.270 --> 01:13:51.770
Yeah.

01:13:51.770 --> 01:13:53.729
One and a half minutes.

01:13:53.729 --> 01:13:55.520
What that means is that
on this time scale,

01:13:55.520 --> 01:13:56.894
if there were two
mRNAs produced,

01:13:56.894 --> 01:13:59.220
they would look
like the same mRNA.

01:13:59.220 --> 01:14:01.810
But from this data
what they conclude

01:14:01.810 --> 01:14:05.940
is that there's typically
only one mRNA produced

01:14:05.940 --> 01:14:09.580
in each protein burst, and
there's not that many protein

01:14:09.580 --> 01:14:12.350
bursts per hour of
the cell division,

01:14:12.350 --> 01:14:14.500
so they won't overlap too much.

01:14:14.500 --> 01:14:17.436
But it's going to
happen at some rate.

01:14:23.900 --> 01:14:24.400
All right.

01:14:28.520 --> 01:14:32.340
What they see is that the
distribution of the protein

01:14:32.340 --> 01:14:36.430
bursts-- we said
it was roughly one

01:14:36.430 --> 01:14:40.720
per cell division time, which
they found was 55 minutes here.

01:14:40.720 --> 01:14:44.280
And they found that the number
of protein bursts per cell

01:14:44.280 --> 01:14:49.160
cycle was distributed Poisson

01:14:49.160 --> 01:14:50.880
So let me write
this down somewhere.

01:15:04.730 --> 01:15:12.140
The number of protein
bursts per cell cycle.

01:15:14.691 --> 01:15:16.190
So this was distributed
as a Poisson

01:15:16.190 --> 01:15:21.950
with mean [INAUDIBLE]
lambda of around 1.

01:15:21.950 --> 01:15:24.300
1.2.

01:15:24.300 --> 01:15:27.220
They call this n cycle.

01:15:27.220 --> 01:15:28.250
So I'll be consistent.

01:15:28.250 --> 01:15:39.320
So this n cycle to the 1.2.

01:15:39.320 --> 01:15:41.860
Now, you guys-- the
Poisson is a distribution

01:15:41.860 --> 01:15:46.810
that we're going to be spending
a lot of time thinking about.

01:15:46.810 --> 01:15:48.830
So the normal way
that we write it

01:15:48.830 --> 01:15:57.030
is that if it's the probability
of observing some number n--

01:15:57.030 --> 01:16:00.674
and this is a number n bursts
per cycle in this case, p of n.

01:16:00.674 --> 01:16:02.090
We normally write
it as a function

01:16:02.090 --> 01:16:06.540
of the mean lambda, where
it's lambda to the n over n

01:16:06.540 --> 01:16:07.412
factorial.

01:16:07.412 --> 01:16:08.870
And then for
normalization, we have

01:16:08.870 --> 01:16:11.630
to write e to the
minus lambda here.

01:16:13.839 --> 01:16:15.630
We're going to spend
a lot of time thinking

01:16:15.630 --> 01:16:19.390
about the Poisson next class.

01:16:19.390 --> 01:16:21.690
So I would say that if it's
been a while since you've

01:16:21.690 --> 01:16:23.564
thought about probability
distributions, then

01:16:23.564 --> 01:16:26.990
you should play via
textbook, Wikipedia, whatnot,

01:16:26.990 --> 01:16:32.770
with the Poisson, the
exponential, the geometric,

01:16:32.770 --> 01:16:34.870
and also the gamma
distributions.

01:16:34.870 --> 01:16:37.335
Because we're going to be
using those in the next class.

01:16:42.670 --> 01:16:45.310
Now, in this distribution,
what it basically

01:16:45.310 --> 01:16:49.080
ends up being is that
sometimes, you see zero bursts.

01:16:49.080 --> 01:16:50.897
Sometimes you see one.

01:16:50.897 --> 01:16:52.230
Every now and then, you see two.

01:16:52.230 --> 01:16:53.700
It's kind of what this means.

01:17:02.660 --> 01:17:05.880
There's one other thing that
is, I think, a bit tricky often,

01:17:05.880 --> 01:17:09.740
which is how they calculated
that it was typically

01:17:09.740 --> 01:17:14.520
one mRNA that led to each
of these proteins bursts.

01:17:14.520 --> 01:17:18.174
Can somebody remind us
kind of experimentally

01:17:18.174 --> 01:17:20.007
what they had to do in
order to get at that?

01:17:26.830 --> 01:17:29.720
The average RNA per cell, right.

01:17:29.720 --> 01:17:32.380
Right, so they did this RT-PCR.

01:17:32.380 --> 01:17:34.940
So what they did, they
reverse transcribed.

01:17:34.940 --> 01:17:37.320
They converted
the mRNA into DNA,

01:17:37.320 --> 01:17:40.000
and they amplified to get a
sense of how much mRNA there

01:17:40.000 --> 01:17:41.860
was.

01:17:41.860 --> 01:17:45.540
And from that, the formula,
when you first look at it,

01:17:45.540 --> 01:17:49.070
it feels kind of mysterious,
or something like that.

01:17:49.070 --> 01:17:51.350
But it's one of those
things that you just

01:17:51.350 --> 01:17:55.360
have to keep track of
like, units and so forth.

01:17:55.360 --> 01:18:00.110
So you can basically think
about the number of mRNA.

01:18:00.110 --> 01:18:04.320
And this is indeed,
this is per cell.

01:18:04.320 --> 01:18:06.490
But cell, this doesn't
have units, right?

01:18:06.490 --> 01:18:09.800
But if we wanted the
expectation value,

01:18:09.800 --> 01:18:12.217
the number of the mRNA
that's going to be per cell,

01:18:12.217 --> 01:18:14.050
well, that's going to
be given by the number

01:18:14.050 --> 01:18:27.140
of the mRNA per burst, times the
number of bursts per unit time.

01:18:31.720 --> 01:18:37.620
So this is some rate
burst, and then also

01:18:37.620 --> 01:18:39.280
times the lifetime of the mRNA.

01:18:46.140 --> 01:18:48.950
Now in this formula, there's
also the added factor,

01:18:48.950 --> 01:18:51.650
where they have like, the
time of the cell cycle.

01:18:51.650 --> 01:18:53.380
But that's just
because this could

01:18:53.380 --> 01:18:56.450
have been bursts per minute,
lifetime of mRNA minutes.

01:18:56.450 --> 01:18:59.170
But then, if you want to
put in the extra term,

01:18:59.170 --> 01:19:01.650
then you have to say, oh,
the cell cycle is 55 minutes.

01:19:01.650 --> 01:19:03.620
So then you have to do
that conversion of time

01:19:03.620 --> 01:19:04.843
into the proper units.

01:19:04.843 --> 01:19:06.218
So that's what
ends up happening.

01:19:17.450 --> 01:19:19.915
Are there any questions
about what happened here?

01:19:25.860 --> 01:19:31.760
Now, what we're going to do
next lecture is kind of go

01:19:31.760 --> 01:19:36.520
through a simplified
model of gene expression,

01:19:36.520 --> 01:19:40.680
where there's just some
rate of mRNA formation, mRNA

01:19:40.680 --> 01:19:44.360
degradation, the mRNA makes
protein, proteins get degraded.

01:19:44.360 --> 01:19:47.275
And then in that model, we
want to try to understand

01:19:47.275 --> 01:19:48.525
how everything is distributed.

01:19:50.802 --> 01:19:52.260
And we're going to
relate that back

01:19:52.260 --> 01:19:54.218
to some of the experimental
data in this paper.

01:19:54.218 --> 01:19:56.860
In particular, for example,
this geometric distribution

01:19:56.860 --> 01:19:59.060
of protein burst
sizes is something

01:19:59.060 --> 01:20:03.560
that you expect from the
most basic simple model

01:20:03.560 --> 01:20:05.160
that you would
have written down.

01:20:05.160 --> 01:20:07.180
So from that same point,
it's not a surprise.

01:20:07.180 --> 01:20:10.300
It is often assumed this
thing should be geometrically

01:20:10.300 --> 01:20:11.590
distributed, and it was.

01:20:11.590 --> 01:20:13.370
And that's wonderful.

01:20:13.370 --> 01:20:15.720
From my standpoint, I think
that even things that we

01:20:15.720 --> 01:20:17.590
